00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:22.090 position:98%
The first I'd like to start with is a short clip of a veteran -

00:02:22.090 --> 00:02:23.990 position:61%
a Vietnam veteran named Artie Guerrero.

00:02:23.990 --> 00:02:28.950 position:88%
Artie was drafted in 1967, was thrown right into combat,

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:31.040 position:66%
and was very seriously wounded in Vietnam.

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:31.840 position:69%
&gt;&gt; Artie Guerrero: I never thought of myself

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:35.920 position:64%
as being courageous, but self-sustaining.

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:42.740 position:98%
That's the part of the animalistic instinct that comes out of you

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:45.510 position:77%
when you're put in a barbaric situation like war.

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:52.710 position:97%
You're not the same civilized mind that you're once taught to be

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:54.580
or the person that you are.

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:56.990 position:58%
And I've suffered these consequences,

00:02:56.990 --> 00:02:59.620 position:59%
and you just don't come back the same.

00:02:59.620 --> 00:03:05.140 position:75%
You suffered the post-traumatic stress disorder.

00:03:05.140 --> 00:03:09.040
It never leaves you.

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:12.440 position:97%
&gt;&gt; Robert Patrick: Artie is wheelchair-bound, but is an advocate

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:14.340
for veterans out in California.

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:17.220 position:64%
