00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:18.740 position:67%
We're told to get the older veterans first.

00:03:18.740 --> 00:03:21.880 position:75%
We have about 48,000 of those from World War II,

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:24.160 position:86%
but we're really starting to focus on Vietnam veterans.

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:27.210 position:97%
They're not getting any younger, either, and we're really hoping

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:28.070
to bring in more and more.

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:31.570 position:80%
We have about 10,000 of those collections here now.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:35.940 position:67%
Now let talk about entertaining the troops,

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:37.310
which I know you're involved with.

00:03:37.310 --> 00:03:39.960
This is Robert Sidney.

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:43.270 position:94%
Robert Sidney is a World War II veteran, and he was enlisted

00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:46.950 position:98%
into the Army to be a part of a show called "This is the Army."

00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:49.370 position:64%
I don't know if you've heard about this -

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:50.070
&gt;&gt; Gary Sinise: Sure, yeah.

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.270 position:83%
&gt;&gt; Robert Patrick: Well, he was their first sergeant,

00:03:52.270 --> 00:03:56.970 position:95%
and Irving Berlin, who set up that show, enlisted him to kind

00:03:56.970 --> 00:03:59.070 position:61%
of be the first sergeant for the troop.

00:03:59.070 --> 00:04:00.490 position:70%
When the show was set up, it was on Broadway.

00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:01.610
It was hit on Broadway.

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:04.590 position:88%
Then they took it over to England, and it was hit there.

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:07.000 position:72%
Played at the Palladium and everyone loved it,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.190 position:66%
but then they were gonna disband the show,

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:11.460
until General Eisenhower showed up.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:12.710 position:72%
&gt;&gt; Robert Sidney: Eisenhower got wind of that,

00:04:12.710 --> 00:04:14.520 position:63%
and that's when he came to see the show.

00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:17.520 position:61%
And after the show, he came back stage.

00:04:17.520 --> 00:04:20.730 position:88%
We were called to attention, and he said, "At ease, men.

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:28.510 position:92%
At ease." And he said, "I want to tell you, I sat out there

00:04:28.510 --> 00:04:33.100 position:97%
in that audience, and if you can do for the GIs what you did for me,

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:35.920 position:72%
brought up so many wonderful memories of home,

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:42.240 position:97%
you're the biggest morale factor we have to offer these men in arms"

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:45.010 position:97%
&gt;&gt; Robert Patrick: What went on then, the show was reconfigured,

00:04:45.010 --> 00:04:47.480
sent literally around the world.

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:52.060 position:98%
